1.2 Load Python

Since Advent of Code says I shouldnât show full inputs, Iâll show a sliced version of my input

import polars as pl
df = pl.read_csv("data/day3.txt", has_header=False).with_columns(
    pl.col("column_1").str.slice(50, 100)
).head(50)
# lines / position

#    | x | 
# ---+---+---
#    | + | 
# ---+---+---
#    | x | 


squares_before_and_after_position = [
    (pl.col("symbol").shift(i).over("position").alias(f"position_{i}")) for i in [-1, 1]
]

# lines / position

#    |   | 
# ---+---+---
#  + | + | +
# ---+---+---
#    |   | 

squares_above_and_below_line = [
    (pl.col("symbol").shift(i).over("line").alias(f"line_{i}")) for i in [-1, 1]
]

# lines / position

#  + |   | +
# ---+---+---
#    |   | 
# ---+---+---
#  + |   | +


squares_diagonals = [
    (
        (
            pl.col("line_-1").shift(i).over("position") | 
            pl.col("line_1").shift(i).over("position")
        ).alias(f"diagonal_{i}") | 
        (
            pl.col("position_-1").shift(i).over("line") | 
            pl.col("position_1").shift(i).over("line")
        ).alias(f"diagonal_{i}")
    )
    for i in [-1, 1]
]

# Single expression to check entire 3x3 area around current position
special_character_in_area = pl.any_horizontal(squares_before_and_after_position + squares_above_and_below_line + squares_diagonals)

working_df = (   
    df.rename({"column_1": "value"})
    .with_columns(pl.col("value").str.split("", inclusive=False).list.slice(1, pl.col("value").len()))
    # Labels the rows/lines ("line")
    .with_row_count(name="line")
    .explode("value")
    # Labels the columns/position within a line ("x")
    .with_row_count(name="position")
    .with_columns(pl.col("position") % df.shape[0])
    .with_columns(
        (~pl.col("value").str.contains(r"(\.|[0-9])")).alias("symbol")
    )
    .with_columns(
        (pl.col("value").str.contains(r"[0-9]")).alias("number")
    )
    .with_columns(
        [cond for cond in squares_above_and_below_line]
    )
    .with_columns(
        [cond for cond in squares_before_and_after_position]
    )
    .with_columns(
        pl.any_horizontal(squares_before_and_after_position + squares_above_and_below_line + squares_diagonals).alias("part")
    )
    # Label "part" squares, and turn "false" into None so I can use pl.coalesce next step.
    .with_columns(
        pl.when(pl.col("part")==True).then(True).otherwise(None).alias("near_special_char")
    )
    .with_columns(
        pl.coalesce("number", "near_special_char").alias("contiguous")
    )
    # If sequential characters are not "contiguous"
    .with_columns(
        group = (pl.col("contiguous") != pl.col("contiguous").shift()).cum_sum()
    )
    .with_columns(
        pl.when(pl.col("contiguous")).then(pl.col("group")).otherwise(pl.lit(None)).alias("number_group")
    )
    # Note "number_group" and "line" - since I am turning it into a long dataframe, need to make sure line 1 that ends with special character
    # don't run into line 2 numbers: This took a while to debug, part of the reason for this data vis
    .with_columns(
        pl.col("near_special_char").over("number_group", 'line', mapping_strategy="join").alias("near_special_char")
    )
    .with_columns(
        pl.when((pl.col("near_special_char").list.any()) & (pl.col("number_group").is_not_null())).then(pl.lit("Part Number"))
        .when(pl.col("symbol")==True).then(pl.lit("Symbol"))
        .when(pl.col("value")==".").then(pl.lit("Period"))
        .otherwise(pl.lit("Removed")).alias("category")
    )
)

2.2 Data Visualization

At this point I just couldnât tell how to âsanity checkâ my results and logic.

Half excuse - I purposely made it extra verbose with sequential .with_columns()

But also because I got very distracted by the visualization.

import altair as alt


alt.data_transformers.disable_max_rows()
DataTransformerRegistry.enable('default')

selection = alt.selection_point(fields=["category"], bind="legend")
selection_2 = alt.selection_point(fields=["line"], on="mouseover")

plot_df = working_df.drop("line_-1", "line_1", "position_-1", "position_1", "part", "near_special_char")

fig = alt.Chart(plot_df).mark_rect(strokeWidth=1).encode(
    x=alt.X("position:O"),
    y=alt.Y("line:O"),
    color=alt.condition(
        selection,
        alt.Color("category:N").scale(scheme="tableau20").legend(
            orient="top",
            labelFontSize=20,
            symbolSize=800,
            labelLimit=1000,
            labelPadding=100,
            titleAlign="center",
        ).title(None),
        alt.value("#f4f4f4")
    ),
    opacity=alt.condition(
        selection_2,
        alt.value(1.0),
        alt.value(0.85)
    ),
    tooltip=[
        alt.Tooltip("position"),
        alt.Tooltip("line"),
        alt.Tooltip("value"),
        alt.Tooltip("category:N")
    ]
)

text = fig.mark_text(size=13).encode(
        text="value",
        color=alt.value("white"),
        stroke=alt.value(None)
)
fig = (
    (fig + text).add_params(selection).add_params(selection_2)
    .properties(
        title=alt.Title(
            "Advent of Code: Day 3",
            subtitle="[Shift + Click] on Legend to Toggle, Double-click to reset",
            fontSize=24,
            anchor="start"
        )
    )
)

fig_json = fig.to_json()

There is a bug with Vega/Quarto renderer that prevents more than 1 chart showing when using both R and Python:

library("vegawidget")

as_vegaspec(py$fig_json)

3 Debugging

3.1 Create the âAnswerâ df

You might need to check whether a value you see needs debugging. Just to showcase Râs reactable.

One of the more common tabular structures for NLP / entity recognition is this type of table that has character positions. I basically turned it into that.

Potentially, you can use this loose structure to reverse-engineer to create the Altair table above.

answer_check_df =(  
    plot_df
    .filter(pl.col("number_group").is_not_null())
    .group_by("number_group", "category", "line")
    .agg(
        pl.max("position").alias("pos_start"),
        pl.min("position").alias("pos_end"),
        pl.col("value").alias("value_concat"))
    .with_columns(
        pl.col("value_concat").list.join("").cast(pl.Int64())
    )
    .sort("line", "number_group")
)
# R only supports pandas conversion so far
answer_check_df = answer_check_df.to_pandas()

4 Reactable Table

Use the search function to search the numbers.

Very simple example but should showcase power of reactable.

library(reactable)
library(htmltools)

answer_check_df <- py$answer_check_df

reactable_table <- (
    reactable(
        answer_check_df,
        searchable = TRUE,
        defaultPageSize = 50,
        defaultSorted = c("line"),
        defaultSortOrder = "asc",
        groupBy = c("category"),
        elementId = "summary_table",
        theme = reactableTheme(
            headerStyle = list(
                "&:hover[aria-sort]" = list(background = "#F5F4F3"),
                "$aria-sort='ascending'], &[aria-sort='descending']" = list(background="#F4F3F3"),
                borderColor = "#555"
            ),
            cellPadding = "4px",
        ),
        style=list(
            fontFamily = "monospace",
            fontSize = "0.8rem",
            paddingTop = "2px",
            paddingBottom = "2px"
        ),
        columns = list(
            number_group = colDef(show=FALSE),
            category = colDef(minWidth=120),
            line = colDef(
                maxWidth=100,
                headerStyle = list(background="#fdae6b"),
                style = list(background="#fee6ce")
            ),
            pos_start = colDef(maxWidth=100),
            pos_end = colDef(maxWidth=100),
            value_concat = colDef(
                minWidth=130,
                aggregate="sum",
                headerStyle=list(background="#ddf2ff"),
                style=list(background="#f1f9ff")
            )
        )
    )
)
